[1] USA (Texas)
Date: 11 Jun 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: CBS KVTV13 [edited]
<http://www.cbs13kvtv.com/news/headlines/821352.html>

The 1st confirmed case of dengue in Laredo [Texas] was found last
week. Laredo health authorities are hoping citizens will take action
in mosquito prevention after a 10-year-old girl caught dengue fever
from a mosquito. Preventing dengue means reducing breeding sites for
mosquitoes. That can be done by getting rid of old tires lying around
your yard or any container that collects standing water, even
swimming pools.
Back in 1999, Laredo and Nuevo Laredo had to deal with an outbreak of
almost 100 cases in Texas and thousands across the border [in Mexico].
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
******
[2] Sri Lanka
Date: 10 Jun 2004
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <arodriguezm@SaludFMV.org>
Source: Yahoo News, UK & AFP [edited]
<http://uk.news.yahoo.com/040610/323/evnt8.html>

Sri Lanka sounds alarm as dengue deaths rise to 24
--------------------------------------------------
Sri Lankan medical authorities expressed fresh alarm after 6 people
died of dengue fever [so far in June 2004], raising to 24 the number
of fatalities during the year.
The number of people infected with the mosquito-borne viral disease
rose to 4348 by Wednesday, up from 3300 at the end of May 2004, said
doctor Hasitha Tissera of the epidemiology unit of the health
ministry.
He said the problem was concentrated in 4 districts, including the
capital Colombo, but dengue cases were now being reported from
throughout the island mainly because of intermittent rains that
helped mosquito breeding.
During 2003, 33 people died of dengue out of 4600 who contracted the
disease, Tissera said, adding 2002 was far worse, with 67 deaths out
of 8900 cases.
Sri Lanka is a dengue-endemic country, and the number of new cases
reported has risen to more than 100 a day, Tissera said.
