[3] Saudi Arabia (Jeddah)
Date: Thu, 10 Jun 2004 10:14:01 +0100 (BST)
From: Shamsudeen Oloungbo <oloungbo@yahoo.com>
Source: Saudi Gazette 10 June 2004 Issue No: 933 [edited]
<http://www.saudigazette.com.sa/sgazette/Data/2004/6/10/Art_115334.XML>

A 35-year-old male Saudi national died of dengue fever at King Fahad
General Hospital in Jeddah on Monday. This is the 1st dengue fever
death to be announced in the city.
In another development, 2 cases were suspected of dengue fever
Tuesday in Jeddah. The 1st case was that of a 28-year-old Saudi woman
who is 7 months pregnant and the 2nd was that of a 22-year-old woman.
They were provided with prescriptions for treatment and their blood
samples were sent to the regional laboratory for testing. The
analysis results are expected to appear during the next 3 days.
Meanwhile, results of analyses of 2 employees in King Abdul Aziz
Hospital showed that they were free from the disease, whereas 4 cases
were confirmed to be afflicted with dengue fever. Of these, 2 were
Saudi nationals who were treated for one week and then released from
hospital.
Abdul Aziz Ali Bouhi, director of Executive Services at King Abdul
Aziz Hospital in Jeddah, said that there is round-the-clock readiness
to receive any dengue fever case. He pointed out that one person was
afflicted with the disease during his visit to another person in the
hospital's residential building. The residence was evacuated and
sprayed fully due to fears of the existence of the carrier mosquito
there.
In another development, Jeddah Municipality carried out an urgent
plan for getting rid of the causes of dengue fever in collaboration
with the other departments concerned. Several insect-combating teams
have intensified the manual spraying operations and are adding
chlorine to stagnant water to get rid of the insect breeding grounds.
About 141 houses and 36 sites for mosquito breeding were inspected
and sprayed; 65 swamps were inspected and 11 stagnant pools were
filled with soil. In addition, the Jeddah mayor issued directives to
monitor the performance of the companies for cleaning and collecting
garbage. Any delay in collecting garbage should be reported, he said.
[Byline: Mohammed Hadhadh]
--
Shamsudeen Oloungbo
<oloungbo@yahoo.com>
******
[4] Saudi Arabia (Jeddah)
Date: Sat, 5 Jun 2004 06:38:03 +0100 (BST)
From: Shamsudeen Oloungbo <oloungbo@yahoo.com>
Source: Arab News 5 June 2004 [edited]
Dr. Talal Ekram, the assistant director at Health Affairs, said a few
days ago that 15 out of 45 suspected cases tested positive for dengue
fever at the Jeddah regional lab.
Dr. Ekram said that dengue fever has been around in Jeddah for 15
years because of the presence of mosquitoes and larval breeding
sites. The rash of new construction projects, where water can gather
without being noticed or drained, presents a particular challenge to
health affairs. Jeddah is full of pools of stagnant water,
overflowing septic tanks, a rising water table coming up through
holes in pavements and on waste ground, leaking sewage tankers,
leaking water pipes and inadequate if not non-existent drainage -- in
other words, a breeding ground for disease-bearing mosquitoes.
Arab News last reported on an outbreak of dengue fever back in August
2003. A committee was supposed to educate residents on ways to fight
mosquitoes. However, it seems that neither the spraying campaign nor
the educational campaign was effective. Dr. Ghazi Sheikh, the
director of preventive health and first aid, said "We're doing what
we can with the spraying, but the unfinished sewage and drainage
system makes it difficult. "
[Byline: Maha Akeel]
--
Shamsudeen Oloungbo
<oloungbo@yahoo.com>
